      property title =
         "Supervisor status register";
      property description =
         "The sstatus register is an SXLEN-bit read/write register keeps "
         "track of the processor’s current operating state. This "
         "register is encoded as follows. All values not shown are "
         "reserved.\n"
         "63: SD.\n"
         "33:32: UXL. The UXL field controls the value of XLEN for U-mode, "
         "termed UXLEN, which may differ from the value of XLEN for "
         "S-mode, termed SXLEN. The encoding of UXL is the same as that of "
         "the MXL field of the misa register. See the misa register for "
         "more information.\n"
         "19: MXR. The MXR (Make eXecutable Readable) bit modifies the "
         "privilege with which loads access virtual memory. When MXR = 0, "
         "only loads from pages marked readable will succeed. When MXR = "
         "1, loads from pages marked either readable or executable (R = 1 "
         "or X = 1) will succeed. MXR has no effect when page-based "
         "virtual memory is not in effect.\n"
         "18: SUM. The SUM (Supervisor User Memory) access bit modifies "
         "the privilege with which S-mode loads and stores access virtual "
         "memory. When SUM = 0, S-mode memory accesses to pages that are "
         "accessible by U-mode will fault. When SUM = 1, these accesses "
         "are permitted. SUM has no effect when page-based virtual memory "
         "is not in effect, nor when executing in U-mode.\n"
         "16:15: XS[1:0]. The XS field represents a summary of all "
         "extensions’ status and is encoded the same as FS[1:0] in bits "
         "14:13.\n"
         "14:13: FS[1:0]. The FS field encodes the status of the "
         "floating-point unit and it encoded as follows: 00: OFF. 01: "
         "INITIAL (none dirty or clean, some on. 10: CLEAN. None dirty, "
         "some clean. 11: DIRTY, some dirty.\n"
         "8: SPP. The SPP bit indicates the privilege level at which a "
         "hart was executing before entering supervisor mode.\n"
         "5: SPIE. The SPIE bit indicates whether supervisor-level "
         "interrupts were enabled prior to taking a supervisor-level trap.\n"
         "4: UPIE. The UPIE bit indicates whether user-level interrupts "
         "were enabled prior to taking a user-level trap.\n"
         "1: SIE. The SIE bit enables or disables all interrupts in "
         "supervisor mode. When SIE is clear, interrupts are not taken "
         "while in supervisor mode.\n"
         "0: UIE. The UIE bit enables or disables all interrupts in user "
         "mode. When SIE is clear, interrupts are not taken while in user "
         "mode. ";
